canonical:
  title: 送仍上人葬其師頓蓭于錦州還京
  author: 尹紹宗
  language: lzh
  text: 海寇極癸亥千山萬山血父子東西奔生死不相恤哀哀仍月江聞亂忘飢渴徒步二千里收拾師尊骨蠒踵冒寇鋒至誠貫白日吾聞浮屠氏人倫一滅絶事師如父母觀者爲感悅月江吾月江執袂未忍別
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 送仍上人葬其師頓蓭于錦州還京
  author: 尹紹宗
  language: lzh
  text: 海寇極癸亥。千山萬山血。父子東西奔。生死不相恤。哀哀仍月江。聞亂忘飢渴。徒步二千里。收拾師尊骨。蠒踵冒寇鋒。至誠貫白日。吾聞浮屠氏。人倫一滅絶。事師如父母。觀者爲感悅。月江吾月江。執袂未忍別。
korean:
  title: 스승 돈암을 금주에 장사 지내고 서울로 돌아가는 잉상인을 보내며
  author: 윤소종
  language: kor
  text: |-
    바다 도적이 계해년에 극도에 달하여
    천산 만산에 피가 흘렀도다
    아비와 자식이 동서로 달아나
    생사간에 서로 돌볼 수 없었거니
    애처롭다, 잉 월강이
    난리 소식 듣고 기갈을 잊고서
    이천 리를 걸어서
    스승의 해골을 수습하였음이여
    발이 부르트며 도적의 칼날 무릅쓰니
    지극한 정성이 흰 해를 꿰었네
    내 들으니 부도씨는
    인륜을 일체로 멸절한다는데
    스승 섬기기를 부모같이 하니
    보는 사람들 감동하고 기뻐하네
    월강 우리 월강
    옷깃을 잡고 차마 이별하지 못하겠네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0080_010_0360&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Sending Off Monk Seung as He Returns to the Capital After Burying His Teacher Donam in Geumju
  author: Yun Seo-jong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sea pirates raged in the year of Gyehae,
    A thousand hills, ten thousand hills ran red with blood.
    Fathers and sons fled east and west,
    In death and life, none could spare a thought for another.

    Poor Seung of the Wolgang River—
    Hearing of chaos, he forgot his hunger and thirst,
    And walked two thousand miles on foot
    To gather the bones of his revered master.

    With blistered heels he braved the brigands' blades,
    His pure heart piercing the white sun itself.
    I have heard that the Buddhist way
    Severs all bonds of kinship and clan,
    Yet he served his teacher as he would his parents—
    All who witness this are moved to tears of joy.

    Seung of the Wolgang, our Seung,
    I cannot bear to release your sleeve and say farewell.
  footnotes:
    - Gyehae (계해년) refers to 1623, during the Later Three Years' War and the Manchu invasions that devastated Korea.
    - Wolgang (월강) is both a place name and a personal epithet, suggesting the monk's connection to water and journey.
    - The reference to Buddhist teaching 'severing all bonds' contrasts with Seung's filial devotion to his teacher, highlighting the poet's admiration for this transcendence of doctrine through human virtue.
